<TEXT>
nicaraguas rebels on monday rejected 
a proposal by the leftist sandinista government to meet in miami to 
resume stalled peace talks but said they would maintain a 
ceasefire indefinitely 
the ussupported rebels called contras proposed that future 
peace talks be held outside nicaragua and that president daniel 
ortega head the government delegation 
a statement issued in miami by the directorate of the nicaraguan 
resistance the contra umbrella group said the rebels set no 
deadline for ending the ceasefire and charged the sandinista 
regime is the one that has signaled a deadline 
a truce that went into effect on march 21 and expired at the end 
of may was unilateraly extended for 30 days by the sandinistas 
that extension puts the truce deadline at june 30 
peace talks between the government and the rebels reached an 
impasse this month over differences on democratic reforms and a 
timetable for the rebels to lay down their weapons 
the last round of negotiations broke off without agreement on 
june 9 
the government proposed that a new round be held this week in 
managua the contras refused saying the capital didnt have a 
favorable atmosphere for negotiations because the government 
wanted to put too many restrictions on rebel negotiators 
the government then suggested a preparatory meeting be held 
tuesday and wednesday in miami to discuss the agenda for the next 
highlevel negotiating session 
the rebel letter issued monday was signed by directorate member 
roberto ferrey and directed to defense minister humberto ortega 
the presidents brother who headed the government team in previous 
negotiating sessions 
a new highlevel meeting should take place to overcome the 
evident lack of political will of the sandinista government in 
complying with a central american peace plan signed by the 
regions five presidents last august the statement said 
that plan authored by costa ricas president oscar arnulfo 
arias called for negotiations aimed at ending civil wars in 
nicaragua el salvador and guatemala arias won the nobel peace 
prize last year for sponsoring the plan 
the contra letter also said any new round of talks would have to 
take place in another central american country and called on 
president ortega to head the government negotiating team 
it said any agreement reached would have to be guaranteed by the 
presidents of el salvador guatemala honduras and costa rica 
the letter to gen ortega said the meeting could not take place 
in nicaragua because of threats even those you have made 
personally and insults made in the sandinista communications media 
against the nicaraguan resistance delegation 
president ortega said in havana cuba on monday that his 
government will keep searching for a negotiated solution to the 
conflict that the united states has imposed upon us he is in 
cuba on a state visit 
</TEXT>
