<TEXT>
the remains of 28 american servicemen found 
in canada in november will be returned to this country for burial 
this week 174 years after they were killed while fighting in the 
war of 1812 
the soldiers will be buried thursday with full military honors 
including a 21gun salute us army officials said a plaque also 
will be placed in the cemetery in the town of bath commemorating 
the soldiers deaths in 1814 during the closing days of the niagra 
campaign the discovery of their remains in 1987 and reburial in 
1988 
these boys will be treated as if they died yesterday said 
lt col robert trotter just because were late doesnt mean 
they wont get what they deserve 
the skeletons were unearthed by construction workers digging a 
house foundation in fort erie ontario across the niagara river 
from buffalo 
archaeologists moved the remains to a toronto laboratory where 
most were identified as americans trotter said 
trotter said hundreds of sites were considered for the 
reburials but military records indicated most of the men were from 
central new york where bath is located 
we figure about 90 percent of the men who fought in the 
niagara campaign were from the finger lakes area he said its 
only right that they should be going home 
although individual indentification of the remains could not be 
made ronald williamson a canadian archaeologist who led the 
investigation said the discovery yielded extensive information 
about the war between the americans and the british 
williamson said most the soldiers were in their teens and early 
20s and died horrible deaths 
the philosophy of medicine at the time was to make a complex 
wound simple if you got shot in the hand they cut off your arm 
he said 
williamson said the soldiers probably died during the daily 
assaults by british mercenaries on a us position at snake hill 
the burial ground was a sandy knoll on the shore of lake erie 
each body showed some preparation before burial indicating that 
the survivors were in a rush he said these probably werent 
battlefield deaths but victims of snipers or artillery barrages in 
the weeks after the main battle 
military records indicate that about five men were lost each day 
during the siege on the position 
the campaign ended weeks later when american forces withdrew and 
the burial ground was apparently forgotten 
</TEXT>
