<TEXT>
theres a new gold rush in the 
california desert powered by 1980s technology for coaxing gold out 
of lowgrade ore but miners are worried that plans for a national 
park could someday end the boom 
in the last five years the amount of gold produced in the 
region has soared from 5000 ounces a year to 300000 and the 
industry is now worth 135 million a year according to the us 
bureau of land management 
there are 15 active mines in the area stretching roughly from 
death valley to the mexican border and seven more awaiting 
approval to start operations according to the blm which manages 
much of the region 
what we are doing down here makes the mother lode look like 
small change said peter ertman who oversees mining for the blm 
in imperial county 
the boom is the result of a decadeold runup in gold prices and 
demand combined with largescale use of a gold extraction technique 
called the heapleach method 
lowgrade ore that wouldnt have been worth exploiting with 
older technology is crushed pushed in to heaps hundreds of yards 
long and more than 10 feet tall and then saturated with a solution 
of cyanide and water the cyanide dissolves or leaches out the 
gold and the water is collected at the bottom of the heap for 
treatment to remove its precious cargo 
but prospectors horizons may be shrunk by a proposal to set 
aside vast areas of the desert as a park and wilderness miners 
told us interior secretary donald hodel at a recent meeting at 
gold fields corps mesquite mine 
a proposal to create a new 15millionacre mojave national 
park and confer wilderness status to 45 million more acres of 
desert would drastically limit areas for exploration said richard 
graeme site manager at the imperial county mine 
the proposal introduced in congress by sen alan cranston 
dcalif excludes existing mines from wilderness or park 
protection 
but hodel and others point out that each site contains finite 
amounts of ore and that miners must move on after using it 
i have two kids who want to grow up to be mining engineers 
graeme said i dont want to see anything happen to preclude them 
from making a positive contribution to the economy of the united 
states 
environmentalists worry that the huge heapleach mines endanger 
the water table and wildlife because the cyanidelaced water runs 
through open troughs from the base of the ore piles to huge open 
ponds where it sits awaiting further processing 
complaints have forced a variety of protective measures 
including laying multiple layers of lining beneath leach piles and 
ponds to keep cyanide out of underground water supplies 
the ponds are enclosed by chainlink fences topped with razor 
wire and reinforced with small mesh at the base to keep out animals 
large and small brightlycolored streamers are draped across the 
ponds and compressedair cannons boom at regular intervals to 
scare away birds 
</TEXT>
