<TEXT>
its 112 degrees in the shade in 
parts of the mojave desert these days but the political heat is 
rising as folks from here to washington fight over a plan to set 
aside 75 million acres as wilderness 
the battleground is a starkly beautiful land of brushy desert 
and craggy mountains stretching from death valley to the mexican 
border from the snowcapped sierra nevada and coast ranges to the 
sandy borders of nevada and arizona 
the rugged 35000squaremile sweep is home to shy bighorn 
sheep the threatened desert tortoise and a few hardworking cattle 
ranchers it has two existing national parks rich lodes of gold 
and minerals and a sprinkling of fiercely independent communities 
park proponents led by sen alan cranston dcalif the sierra 
club and the wilderness society see the desert as a fragile 
treasure already scarred beyond recovery in some spots by mine 
pits and recreational vehicles 
they would set aside a slice of varied desert terrain bigger 
than the state of delaware as mojave national park 
and they would designate as wilderness areas 80 spots deemed 
ecologically sensitive biologically unique or just beautiful 
including the south algadones dunes the orocopia mountains the 
saline valley and the mecca hills 
even opponents agree the desert deserves special reverence 
its not the dollar value said cattleman dave fisher 
sipping a beer at a barbecue thrown by ranchers worried the bill 
might drastically limit livestock grazing on federal land its 
the greatness of a way of life my god look at that sky look 
across the top of them old pinon trees this is gods country 
leading the fight against the bill is us interior secretary 
donald hodel who toured the region last week 
hodel believes mojave national park would unfairly exclude 
hunters prospectors and explorers he also backs a bureau of land 
management recommendation to limit designated wilderness areas to 
44 covering less than half the area envisioned by cranston 
government land outside park and wilderness should be open to 
multiple use say hodel and the blm meaning vehicles could 
traverse unmaintained roads and tracks and selected mining and 
grazing would be allowed 
i just dont think we have to choose between either preserving 
and protecting on the one hand and natural resources 
transportation corridors and the rest on the other hand hodel 
said we can do both 
park backers nervously monitor the encroachment of civilization 
from los angeles and san diego 
what is the megalopolis of southern california going to need 
in its back yard 100 years from now muses jim dodson sierra 
club desert coordinator and resident of the booming desert suburb 
of lancaster my feeling is if we dont set these areas aside 
right now my grandchildren wont have any opportunities 
the two sides line up like this 
the mojave national park would cover 15 million acres of the 
eastern mojave desert next to the nevada border between interstates 
10 and 40 the blm wants the same land declared a national scenic 
area allowing carefully regulated offroad vehicles cattle 
grazing and other commercial activities that wouldnt be permitted 
in a park 
cranstons proposal dubbed s7 after its senate bill number 
would make 45 million acres of wilderness offlimits for vehicles 
and new mining the blm is proposing 44 wilderness areas totaling 2 
million acres 
death valley national monument would be expanded from 21 
million acres to 34 million acres under s7 and joshua tree 
national monument would grow from 600000 acres to 800000 the blm 
favors less extensive expansions of both parks 
the debate is complex mixing economic and national security 
concerns with the battle over recreation 
one issue is the fate of fourwheeldrive routes the vehicles 
would be limited to established roads in parks and banned from 
wilderness areas 
it would fence out old people young people people with 
physical impairments said carmelita swarts a san diego retiree 
who has roamed the desert by jeep collecting agates jasper and 
petrified wood 
bill backers say proposed wilderness boundaries were carefully 
drawn so that 85 percent of the wilderness would be within 3 miles 
of a road or track that would remain open to vehicles 
the blm estimates that s7 would close 2200 of the 21000 miles 
of unmaintained but passable dirt roads and tracks in the area 
covered by the bill while the sierra club puts the mileage at 
1200 
about 5000 acres would remain open for riding across country 
mining also would be affected new technology that extracts gold 
from lowgrade ore has brought a mineral boom each year about 
135 million in gold is mined in the desert along with other 
minerals that bring the total mining take to 12 billion 
s7 supporters say they drew park and wilderness boundaries to 
leave known mineralrich areas in the clear but mining executives 
worry that wilderness designation which forbids new exploration 
could close off rich areas 
four big military bases in the desert provide troop training and 
testing grounds for planes and missiles 
military brass who limit lowlevel flights over park and 
wilderness areas worry that s7 would hem their bases in with 
wilderness pressuring them to further limit flights 
the sierra clubs dodson a civilian air force employee said 
flight assurances can be written into the law 
the battle appears unlikely to be resolved in the present 
session of congress environmentalists hope the next presidential 
administration will look more favorably on the park 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

