<TEXT>
after a month of speeches and debate on 
disarmament un delegates were unable to agree on the future 
direction of arms control and adjourned their special general 
assembly session in failure 
many of the 135 speakers at the session hailed the recent 
ussoviet treaty to scrap all intermediaterange nuclear 
missiles yet they were unable to emulate the superpowers and 
overcome national policy differences 
different nations and regional groups held a variety of 
conflicting views but the crucial rift developed between sweeping 
proposals advanced by the soviet union and developing nations and a 
more cautious approach backed by the united states and some of its 
western allies 
delegates clashed in debate over issues such as the us 
spacebased missile defense system known as star wars un 
monitoring of landbased weapons and disarmament and a soviet call 
for a joint ussoviet nuclear test ban 
by sunday morning they gave up the attempt to write a mutually 
acceptable document no vote was attempted on the final resolution 
the 159member general assembly has no enforcement power over 
its decisions but delegates believed a final resolution adopted by 
consensus would carry moral authority by expressing the will of 
the world community 
chinese delegate yu mengyia seemed to blame the united states 
when he said a certain country which should have important 
disarmament responsibilities had insisted on its position that was 
a major reason that consensus was not achieved 
speaking for the soviet union vladimir f petrovsky said only 
that no consensus was possible because of the actions of some 
states 
us delegate max friedersdorf said his country regretted very 
much that it had not been possible to achieve consensus on the 
chairmans draft document which had been acceptable in large part 
to most delegations 
the delegates attempted to rewrite the final document 
unanimously approved at the first special general assembly session 
on disarmament 10 years ago a utopian resolution that many nations 
consider an important outline of the goal of a weaponsfree world 
an attempt to revise the document at the second special session 
on disarmament in 1982 ended in disagreement 
american and some other western allies indicated during the 
latest session that they would reject any document that did not 
address basic concerns of the west including 
spiraling military spending by developing nations western 
delegates said those funds would be better spent on economic 
development education and health care 
the emergence of regional powers as major factors in 
militarization and instability such as iran and iraq and india 
and pakistan virtually all wars since world war ii have been 
fought among developing nations 
recognizing that the united states and the soviet union have 
made progress on disarmament and stating that such treaties are a 
strictly bilateral matter as us secretary of shultz george 
shultz told the special session 
in addition the united states favored emphasis on conventional 
disarmament especially in europe where the warsaw pact is regarded 
as stronger than nato in such forces 
in his speech to the session soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze called for elimination of all nuclear weapons by the 
end of the century troop reductions of 500000 soldiers each by 
the warsaw pact and nato and a joint ussoviet nuclear test ban 
the soviets and the developing nations also favored an expanded 
role for the united nations in arms control monitoring and an 
international naval force under un control which the united 
states opposes 
nonaligned nations further wanted to identify israel and south 
africa as regional offenders in the final document another bone of 
contention with the west 
the special session cost the financially ailing world body 74 
million 
