<DOCNO> AP880627-0079 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today loosened the 
requirements for law enforcement agents to first obtain court 
warrants before conducting searches on private property 
the justices split 43 in ruling that evidence initially 
discovered during an unlawful search sometimes may be used at trial 
if the same evidence is rediscovered during a second lawful 
search 
the courts three dissenters said the ruling emasculates the 
warrant clause of the constitutions fourth amendment which 
generally requires police to get a courts permission before 
conducting searches 
in a 1984 decision the court significantly relaxed the search 
warrant requirement 
in that case police had entered a drug suspects apartment 
without first getting a warrant during a brief search they saw 
some drug paraphernalia 
only after the initial warrantless entry did the officers 
obtain a warrant the police did not tell the magistrate who issued 
the warrant about their previous search 
during their second search of the apartment the police found 
illegal drugs 
the supreme court although finding the first search unlawful 
said the drugs confiscated during the second search could be used 
as trial evidence because the search warrant had been issued on 
grounds unrelated to what police saw during the first unlawful 
search 
in that 1984 decision the justices said police would not be 
encouraged to conduct illegal searches because officers who enter 
illegally will recognize that whatever evidence they discover as a 
direct result of the entry may be suppressed as evidence 
in the case decided today fbi agents conducted an april 6 1983 
search of a south boston warehouse without first obtaining a search 
warrant 
the agents saw but did not seize 270 bales of marijuana 
they then got a warrant reentered the warehouse and seized the 
marijuana 
in upholding the use of the seized marijuana as trial evidence 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals noted that the fbi agents did 
not depend on anything seen during their first entry in obtaining 
the search warrant 
but lawyers for two men convicted in connection with the 
marijuana seizure michael f murray and james d carter argued 
that the 1984 rulings language about evidence discovered as a 
direct result of an unlawful entry should control their case 
the two men were sentenced to four years in prison and fined 
15000 each for conspiring to possess marijuana with intent to 
distribute it 
writing for the court today justice antonin scalia said the 
marijuana does not have to be excluded as evidence if the fbi 
agents would have sought a warrant to search the warehouse even if 
they had not entered unlawfully the first time 
the case now returns to a federal trial judge who will have to 
make that determination 
so long as a later lawful seizure is genuinely independent of 
an earlier tainted one there is no reason why the seized 
evidence should not be used at trial scalia said 
he was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white and harry a blackmun 
justices thurgood marshall john paul stevens and sandra day 
oconnor dissented 
in a opinion for the three marshall said when the very law 
enforcement officers who participate in an illegal search 
immediately thereafter obtain a warrant to search the same 
premises i believe the evidence discovered during the initial 
illegal entry must be suppressed from use at trial 
the case is murray vs us 86995 and 861016 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

