<TEXT>
the spooks who torment the major characters 
in tennessee williams the night of the iguana never seem very 
threatening in the mild revival which arrived sunday at the circle 
in the square theater 
the drama first performed in new york in 1961 simmers in 
obvious symbolism but this production hampered by miscasting and 
perfunctory staging doesnt even capitalize on the plays more 
florid poetry it dilutes williams story eliminating much of the 
passion and leaving only the bare bones of the story 
the time is 1940 the setting is a dilapidated tourist hotel on 
the western coast of mexico and the iguana of the title is a 
trapped creature tied up and kept under the hotel porch where it 
is being fattened up as a future meal 
the main characters also are trapped bound by their own fears 
and failures chief among these neurotic captives is the rev t 
lawrence shannon a defrocked minister reduced to leading bible 
belt ladies on thirdrate bus tours of the mexican countryside 
shannon seeks refuge from the harridans on his tour in the hotel 
which is run by maxine a lusty and cynical widow among the other 
residents are the worlds oldest living poet struggling to 
write a final poem and the poets unmarried granddaughter who 
despite her spiritual quality displays a practicality that enables 
her to survive 
the exminister must battle his desire for liquor and 
particularly young girls a failing that has gotten him into 
trouble once again when the curtain rises as shannon explains 
when you live on the fantastic level as i have lately but have 
got to operate on the realistic level thats when youre spooked 
thats the spook 
nicolas surovy who plays the dissolute shannon doesnt capture 
the mans pain and weariness at having to perpetually struggle 
besides looking too young and healthy for the role surovy 
never manages to suggest that here is a man ready for death 
willing even to swim out to sea and drown if he could lose his 
problems 
equally unconvincing is jane alexander in the role originated on 
broadway by bette davis and in the movie version by ava gardner 
miss alexander seems uncomfortable as the blowsy maxine maybe 
wishing she were playing hannah the ethereal spinster maria 
tucci in the revivals best performance manages to portrayt 
hannahs steely resolve as well as her desperation at not knowing 
what will happen after her grandfather dies 
william lemassena doesnt suggest the mental and physical 
deterioration of the old poet but a comic pamela paytonwright 
exudes the proper shrillness as the most vocal of the irate 
tourists on shannons tour 
the lush tropical setting by zack brown spills nicely across the 
theaters elongated stage filled with rocks leafy plants and 
exotic trees but director theodore mann doesnt utilize the set 
at times the characters stand around awkwardly looking like they 
are staring into a black void rather than conversing with another 
person on stage 
the production ends up being a literal static remounting of the 
play without the fire that should ignite the story this night 
of the iguana ends up as a long snooze rather than a compelling 
drama of coping with personal demons that never will go away 
what other critics said 
in the new york times mel gussow wrote unsteadily guided by 
mr mann the production seems alternately languorous and 
heavyhanded the costa verde is in place with all its out of 
season seediness ready to welcome its disparate lonely 
characters but with the definite exception of ms tucci the 
theatrical hotel is not amply inhabited 
howard kissel in the daily news said watching tennessee 
williams night of the iguana i kept wondering if ted mann who 
directed it and who runs circle in the square which recently 
presented a lame streetcar wants to do to williams what joe papp 
is doing to shakespeare present his plays so flatly youd never 
know the author was a poet 
clive barnes of the new york post wrote in the final 
count it lacks something in urgency and anxiety partly because of 
the conventionally distraught but essentially bland portrayal given 
by nicolas surovy as shannon this is still a play in search of 
its ultimate definition a definition that cannot come oddly 
enough until a great and perhaps bizarre actor shows us how 
the play can really work 
