<TEXT>
the supreme court today gave communities 
nationwide broader power to ban picketing of private residences 
by a 63 vote the court said such bans do not necessarily 
violate freespeech rights 
the decision is a defeat for antiabortion activists who were 
barred from picketing a doctors home in the milwaukee suburb of 
brookfield wis 
the ruling could also represent a significant setback for unions 
locked in labor disputes 
in another case the court gave defense contractors important 
protection against lawsuits by people who accuse them of making 
defective equipment that causes death or injury 
the justices by a 54 vote refused to reinstate a 725000 
award to the family of a marine helicopter copilot who died in a 
1983 crash in the atlantic ocean near virginia beach va 
in the picketing case a brookfield ordinance that outlaws 
picketing before or about the residence or dwelling of any 
individual is tailored narrowly enough to protect freedom of 
speech while protecting residents privacy the court said 
justice sandra day oconnor writing for the court said the 
ordinance is limited to picketing taking place solely in front of 
a particular residence 
so narrowed the ordinance permits the more general 
dissemination of a message oconnor said general marching 
through residential neighborhoods or even walking a route in front 
of an entire block of houses is not prohibited by this ordinance 
but justice john paul stevens in a dissenting opinion said 
brookfields ordinance makes it unlawful for a fifth grader to 
carry a sign saying get well charlie our team needs you in 
front of a residence for a period of time necessary to convey its 
friendly message to its intended audience 
an antiabortion group the milwaukee coalition for life 
demonstrated in front of dr benjamin victorias home in brookfield 
on at least six occasions in 1985 
victoria performs abortions as part of his medical practice in 
milwaukee and appleton wis 
the demonstrators carried signs protesting abortion and shouted 
slogans such as dr victoria youre a killer 
the demonstrations ranged in size from 11 to more than 40 people 
in the month that the picketing occurred the brookfield town 
board enacted the disputed ordinance challenged in court by 
demonstrators sandra c schultz and robert l braun 
us district judge john w reynolds in milwaukee barred 
brookfield from enforcing the ordinance by issuing a preliminary 
injunction 
he ruled that the ordinance probably is unconstitutional because 
a public street is the type of traditional public forum where a 
flat ban on speech cannot be tolerated 
an evenly divided 7th us circuit court of appeals upheld the 
injunction 
today the supreme court reversed the appeals court ruling 
because the picketing prohibited by the brookfield ordinance 
is speech directed primarily at those who are presumptively 
unwilling to receive it the town has a substantial and 
justifiable interest in banning it oconnor said 
the nature and scope of this interest make the ban narrowly 
tailored the ordinance also leaves open ample alternative channels 
of communication and is contentneutral she said 
ms schultz head of the milwaukee coalition for life said i 
understand that marching is still okay and we can go up and down 
the block a little further im a little confused about the 
distinction and how far we have to go down the street before its 
legal so we will just change our tactics and go a little 
further down the street it wont deter our movement 
harold furhman an attorney hired by town of brookfield said 
im very delighted with the decision and feel that it is 
consistent with the argument throughout both in our oral 
arguments and in our briefs 
no matter what form or type of speech is involved past court 
rulings have let government place reasonable restrictions on the 
time place or manner of expression 
but such restrictions must be contentneutral be narrowly 
tailored serve a significant governmental interest and leave open 
alternate channels for communicating the same message 
during oral arguments last april fuhrman contended for 
brookfield that the ordinance was aimed only at pickets who 
concentrated on one particular home and not at those who chose to 
parade through a residential neighborhood with their messages 
the justices appeared then to find signficance in that 
interpretation of the ordinance and in the fact that the 
antiabortion group was free to picket victoria at his places of 
business or in brookfields two commercial areas 
at one point during the april argument session justice antonin 
scalia said to the demonstrators lawyer you want to harass this 
doctor you want to stick your thumb in his eye isnt that what 
this is all about 
oconnors opinion adopted fuhrmans interpretation of the 
ordinance 
brookfields ordinance had been defended in 
friendofthecourt briefs submitted by the national league of 
cities the us conference of mayors and the national association 
of counties 
the picketers were supported by an unusual coalition of 
organizations including the american civil liberties union the 
antiabortion american life league christian advocates serving 
evangelism and the aflcio 
joining oconnor in upholding the ordinance were chief justice 
william h rehnquist and justices harry a blackmun byron r 
white antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
joining stevens in dissent were justices william j brennan and 
thurgood marshall 
in other action the court 
loosened the requirements for law enforcement agents to first 
obtain court warrants before conducting searches on private 
property 
the justices split 43 in ruling that evidence initially 
discovered during an unlawful search sometimes may be used at trial 
if the same evidence is rediscovered during a second lawful 
search 
agreed to decide whether military veterans disability 
benefits indirectly may be subjected to a states community 
property law when they divorce 
the court said it will review a ruling that californias 
required splitting of benefits with exspouses does not violate 
federal law 
let stand a ruling that grants an exemption from state sales 
taxes to highstakes bingo games run by indian tribes 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by oklahoma 
officials seeking to impose the tax on revenue from a bingo game in 
tulsa run by the muscogee creek nation 
agreed to decide whether prison officials sometimes must 
explain why they bar an inmate from having visitors 
the justices said they will study a federal appeals court ruling 
that a kentucky prisons visitation program created a liberty 
interest for inmates that cannot be infringed without due process 
said federal judges have substantial authority to award fees 
to lawyers who win suits against the government 
the justices voting 62 said a california antipoverty law 
firm is entitled to recover legal fees for successfully challenging 
the withholding of federal housing subsidies 
the picketing case is frisby vs schultz 87168 
