republican george bush is facing the worst 
of both worlds a new poll suggested monday getting little help 
from voters satisfaction with the shortterm state of the economy 
while being hurt by fears about the longterm fate of the nation 
the vice president trails democrat michael dukakis in the survey 
conducted for the times mirror corp however the massachusetts 
governor is not well known to most of the public and that gives 
bush an opening to tighten the race in the fall said analyst 
norman ornstein 
this poll doesnt tell who will win the election ornstein 
told reporters for most americans michael dukakis is a blank 
slate in the next couple of months there will be a lot written on 
the slate and not just by dukakis but also by the media and by 
george bush and the republicans 
the survey the latest in a series for the media company 
conducted by the gallup organization is based on interviews with 
3021 adults in person from may 1322 the margin of potential 
sampling error was two percentage points 
the horserace numbers for the poll gave dukakis 53 percent of 
the registered voters and bush 40 percent seven percent were 
undecided 
bushs relatively weak showing could be partly a result of being 
saddled with the role of vice president but conventional wisdom 
would also suggest that he should benefit from the nations 
economic prosperity during the final six years of the reagan 
administration 
indeed many people are optimistic about their own finances and 
the national economy over the coming year fiftyfour percent think 
they will be personally better off next year while only 10 percent 
say their financial situation will deteriorate 
twentyfour percent think the national economy will improve in 
the next year while 46 percent believe there will be little 
change twenty percent are pessimistic 
but ornstein said bush has gotten the worst of both worlds 
pointing to poll findings that the public is very concerned about 
the longterm future and a feeling that things are out of control 
only 41 percent of the public was satisfied with the way 
things are going in the country while 54 percent were 
dissatisfied the poll said 
an indicator of the depth of the fears was the finding that 37 
percent said it is likely or certain that the us economy could 
collapse in the next 10 years because of foreign competition 
thus bush is not getting a boost from the economic picture 
while he is suffering from concerns about the reagan 
administrations stewardship 
fortythree percent of those questioned said the democratic 
party can bring about the kinds of changes the country needs 
with only 27 percent labeling the gop that way nine percent said 
both parties 11 percent said neither and 10 percent were not sure 
and this gives dukakis much of his strength 
democrats are seen as the party of change bush is not said 
andrew kohut president of the gallup organization 
overall dukakis drew a favorable response from 66 percent of 
the sample while 22 percent rated him unfavorably bush got 51 
percent positive marks and 42 percent negative 
but the dukakis numbers are the result of a vague mildly 
positive image the poll analysis said pointing out that 
relatively few voters could rate dukakis on a range of specific 
characteristics 
bushs image is a bit clearer since he has been on the national 
scene longer but he is stuck with some strong negatives and 
relatively few positives the analysis said 
asked in the poll if they were voting more for their candidate 
or against his opponent bush backers were mostly positive of his 
40 percent support 26 percentage points were based on probush 
sentiments and 11 percent antidukakis three percent were not sure 
but half of dukakis supporters took a negative stance of 
dukakis 53 percent only 22 percentage points were produkakis 26 
percent were antibush and the rest were not sure 
the times mirror surveys over the past year have divided the 
public into 11 groups based on their values and partisan 
affiliation 
dukakis is doing well in part because he is drawing strong 
support from usually democratic groups in fact the poll said that 
democrats are slightly more loyal to dukakis at this point than 
republicans are to bush a dramatic change from the high rates of 
democratic defection in recent decades at the presidential level 
bush has solid backing from key gop groups but the vice 
president has not won the strong support ronald reagan had in a 
group the poll calls the disaffecteds those who are 
pessimistic and deeply suspicious of both big government and big 
business 
