follow the broad outlines set earlier by the partys policymaking 
central committee 
gorbachev announced in january 1987 that he wanted to call a 
general conference the first since 1941 and only the 19th in 
communist party history for months afterward officials and 
reformers suggested that radical changes would be decided at the 
forum which was seen as a watershed for the kremlins new policies 
slogans fluttering all over moscow talk of a revolutionary 
change and officials insist the conference will help make 
gorbachevs perestroika or restructuring irreversible 
but they concede it is unlikely that some of the most radical 
reforms proposed in weeks of fervent discussion in the staterun 
media will be approved at the conference 
there is a lot of waiting for a miracle said otto latsis a 
conference delegate and deputy editor of the monthly journal 
kommunist but you cant expect that the day after the 
conference we will wake up in paradise 
latsis comments reflected a general effort by party officials 
and reforms in recent days to play down expectations that the 
conference would fundamentally change the course of society 
diplomats and other foreign analysts suggested the tactic was 
intended to make any gains gorbachev does make for his reform 
policy appear as a significant strengthening of his leadership 
position 
latsis said the forum wont decide on specifics of economic 
policy but will concentrate on uniting the party behind a new 
definition of the communists role in soviet society 
the original proposals for the conference known as theses were 
published last month after being approved by the central committee 
on may 23 
the theses contained a few specific proposals for reform such 
as limiting office holders to a maximum of two fiveyear terms in 
any one post and a much broader but more vague program to 
dismantle the remnants of the authoritarian rule of josef v stalin 
the stalinist past is likely to be a topic of discussion as the 
party tries to determine its role following gorbachevs calls for 
communists to withdraw from daytoday administration and play a 
more political role in setting general goals for society 
echoing soviet founder vladimir i lenins slogan of all power 
to the soviets the theses suggest that the power of the local 
governing councils known as soviets should be strengthened 
latsis told reporters he believed workers in the party apparatus 
should be barred from election to the councils in an effort to 
divide power and increase the accountability of the communist party 
but more conservative voices have insisted the party must keep 
firm control over all aspects of society as it has for most of the 
70 years since the 1917 revolution 
some reformers had predicted the conference would elect a new 
central committee enabling gorbachev to weed out oldtimers and 
install younger more dynamic figures on the policysetting body 
yuri a sklyarov head of the central committees propaganda 
department said monday however that the election of new central 
committee members is not on the conference agenda 
there are 60 to 70 dead souls among the 300plus members on 
the central committee dead souls are those who have either 
died or lost the jobs that entitled them to seats since the last 
central committee was elected in 1986 
sklyarov suggested thursday that new members might join the key 
body but he and another central committee official georgy 
kryuchkov said monday there was no reason why people who had 
retired from previous posts should lose their central committee 
seats now 
</TEXT>
