<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency has found 
tanks lined with lead solder in eight of 12 water coolers 
manufactured by a company that said it had never used lead tanks or 
leadlined tanks according to documents made available by a 
congressional source 
water from one of the tanks was contaminated with lead 40 times 
the current epa drinking water standard and 100 times the 
standard expected to be adopted later this year 
rep henry waxman dcalif chairman of the health and 
environment subcommittee of the house energy and commerce 
committee last week asked te company halsey taylor of freeport 
ill to recall the coolers to repair or replace the tanks 
the environmental protection agency testing water coolers from 
two navy installations in maryland last year found high 
concentrations of lead in their water 
this discovery led to a survey of manufacturers by the 
subcommittee which estimated in february that close to a million 
tanks had lead solder in their plumbing connections 
several models of halsey taylor coolers used lead solder on 
connections between 1978 and late last year but president robert 
a hoagland wrote waxman in january that the company never 
designed or manufactured a water cooler that used a leadlined 
or lead tank 
of 22 tanks provided by the navy for testing 12 were made by 
halsey taylor and eight had tanks lined with lead solder according 
to a letter from michael cook head of the water office at epa to 
a company official 
halsey taylor a subsidiary of household international inc 
inspected 14000 coolers in 1979 repairing many with pinhole leaks 
that had permitted solder to get inside 
cook said he did not know why solder would be used for a lining 
its conceivable the tanks had similar leaks but it doesnt 
look like it the solder is in a uniform layer inside cook said 
the solder is 50 percent lead and 50 percent other metals he 
said epa has offered to provide parts of the tank for the company 
to test and is awaiting a response he said 
the companys director of marketing tom klein said he believed 
cooks assessment was wrong the tanks in question probably came 
from the 1979 batch and might easily have developed a uniform 
coating inside klein said 
we are not hiding our head in the sand we are cooperating 
with congressman waxman said klein 
one of the tanks provided a sample containing 2000 parts per 
billion of lead according to cooks letter the maximum 
permissible lead concentration is 50 parts per billion and epa 
expects to lower that to 20 parts per billion 
two coolers with solderlined tanks were missing identification 
tags the other six carried model numbers wt8a gc10a and gc10acr 
according to cooks letter 
lead is a poison that in high enough concentrations can damage 
the brain and other organs children are particularly vulnerable 
because their brains are still developing 
until 1986 solder used on copper pipes in homes contained lead 
and many older cities have lead pipes in their water systems 
people should not be preoccupied with water coolers said 
cook in addition to all the other possible sources he said we 
have increasing evidence that brass fittings in homes do contribute 
lead in the very first water you get when turn on the tap after it 
has been idle 
epa has estimated that 42 million americans use tap water 
containing lead above 20 ppb of which 38 million are children 
under age 6 an estimated 241000 children under 6 are getting 
enough lead to harm them the agency estimates 
rep gerry sikorski dminn planned to introduce a bill today 
requiring epa to help schools test and renovate water systems 
contaminated by lead forbidding the sale of leadcontaining 
coolers and requiring manufacturers to recall any previously sold 
and forcing epa to make the new standard 10 ppb instead of 20 ppb 
the water test corp of manchester nh wrote waxman it would 
test samples without charge for schools that request it schools 
would have to get sample bottles from the company and pay shipping 
charges 
