recommends that medicaid be expanded to cover 27 million more poor 
people the federalstate program now serves about 19 million poor 
elderly blind and disabled 
members of the amas house of delegates are expected to act on 
the report during the convention which runs monday through 
thursday 
the medicaid program is totally inadequate to address the 
problem of uninsured and underinsured people in the united 
states said dr william hotchkiss outgoing ama president as 
physicians we feel we must take the position of advocates for 
making health care available to all lowincome people 
the report proposes a massive overhaul of the medicaid program 
at an estimated annual cost of 24 billion it calls for expanding 
medicaid to provide coverage for medical care to an estimated 27 
million people who are living at or below the poverty level but not 
receiving government healthcare benefits 
at 1988 spending levels the amas proposal would raise 
medicaids cost from 52 billion to 76 billion but it doesnt 
recommend how to pay for the increase 
i think its a laudable attempt by the ama to address the 
issue of how we provide medical care to the poor and working poor 
of our country said dean schott a spokesman for the illinois 
department of public aid which administers the program in this 
state 
but the ama i think has an obligation to also suggest how 
this program would be funded do we raise taxes to pay for it do 
we shift money from one program to another schott said sunday 
the ama study found that an estimated 60 percent of us 
residents whose incomes are below the national poverty level dont 
qualify for medicaid because the eligibility standards vary widely 
between states 
to reduce these inequities the ama proposes creating uniform 
national standards of eligibility and uniform payments for medical 
care 
when the federal goverment established medicaid in 1965 it 
failed to set uniform standards and any changes in the program 
would require its approval 
