<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to decide 
whether states may tax federal pensions while exempting the 
pensions of retired state workers 
the court said it will hear an appeal by a michigan man seeking 
a 4299 refund from the state 
paul s davis of east lansing is seeking the refund for state 
taxes he paid from 1979 through 1984 davis a lawyer worked for 
the federal government at various times in his career retiring in 
1980 
michigan law allows federal retirees living in the state to 
deduct up to 7500 in their annual government pensions when 
computing what they owe in state taxes 
the law permits retired state workers to deduct all of their 
state pensions from their state taxes 
the michigan court of appeals in 1987 upheld the statute it 
said the state law does not violate a federal law in which congress 
allowed states to tax federal pay or compensation if the 
taxation does not discriminate against federal workers 
the state court also said the different treatment in pensions is 
justified by michigans legitimate policy of recruiting and keeping 
state employees 
the reagan administration supported davis appeal to the supreme 
court 
the justice department said the fact that the discrimination 
at issue here gives the state a competitive edge does not 
distinguish it from any other special tax benefit given to those 
who deal with the state rather than the federal government and does 
not justify the discrimination 
the case is davis vs michigan department of treasury 871020 
