<TEXT>
a major magnetic storm that would have 
disrupted radio communications did not occur monday fulfilling a 
revised forecast that scientists issued in the wake of the largest 
solar flare in four years 
it has not caused any problems that we are aware of said 
michael abbott a forecaster at the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administrations space environmental laboratory in 
boulder 
on friday after a nearly twohour flare forecasters predicted 
a storm that would cause major disruptions to shortwave including 
shoretoshore communications polar communications and contact 
between airliners and ground controllers as well as longdistance 
telephone calls 
but they downgraded that original forecast saturday and amended 
it again sunday 
gary heckman noaas space environment services chief had said 
when the storm warning was issued friday that forecasting such 
disturbances was tricky 
hot gases and electrically charged particles emitted by solar 
flares contain their own magnetic field which must be pointed in 
the right direction to interact with earths magnetic field to 
cause a magnetic storm heckman said 
abbott said the region on the sun that caused the large flares 
has begun rotating away from the earth we dont expect any more 
significant activity from this region he said 
but he said another region that will be pointed toward the earth 
for the next 14 days could produce some activity 
noaa officials in boulder predicted the serious storm friday 
after the largest solar flare in four years exploded on the sun 
fridays solar flare an explosive release of hot gas 
electrically charged particles and xrays began at 1044 am mdt 
and lasted for nearly two hours scientists said 
dale gary a solar astronomer at the california institute of 
technology in pasadena said it was the biggest flare since april 
1984 with its visible portion extending perhaps 200000 miles 
above the suns surface 
