<TEXT>
the city council will consider banning 
skateboarding only in the downtown business district after both 
youths and grownups objected monday to the idea of a citywide 
prohibition on the popular sport 
in chambers packed with concerned skateboarders ages 8 to 32 
mayor bill frederick said the council had decided to rewrite a bill 
and scale down the proposed ban 
city officials police and property owners said they were 
concerned with safety property damage and vandalism in initially 
proposing a prohibition on all public streets sidewalks and 
property 
we need to build a place where we can all skate we can 
work together for it said 16yearold rick andrews 
his comments typified the sentiment of the crowd of 50 to 60 
young people appearing at city hall to protest the proposal 
the youngsters many in shorts and tshirts and some carrying 
their skateboards into the council chambers said damage and 
vandalism were restricted to a small percentage of people and 
resulted from not having any place in which they could practice the 
popular sport 
the young people got support from a number of parents and other 
grownups 
only one person spoke up for a limited ban but he too said the 
city should work with skateboarders businessmen and property 
owners toward the construction of skate parks or ramps 
calling the revised plan a major change in direction the 
mayor said the city was concerned about its liability if it built a 
skateboarding area but he urged the youths to form a committee to 
work with city officials on an ordinance and a possible park 
gene groves an active skateboarder told the commission that 
skateboarding is a principal form of transportation for many 
young people particularly those too young to drive 
he and others said other florida cities such as ocala tampa and 
jacksonville had public and private skateboard parks and orlando 
should too 
the council action monday puts the issue back into the 
discussion stage further meetings will be held before it comes up 
for another public hearing 
under the proposal skateboarding also would be outlawed on 
private property such as parking lots without permission from the 
owners violators would face a maximum fine of 500 and 60 days in 
jail 
