<TEXT>
 
editors note most people want to live as long as possible and 
most want the benefits of the healing arts but what of those who 
stricken by terminal illness think otherwise and those who 
incapable of decisions themselves linger hopelessly to the 
distress of their families few questions raise greater 
difficulties or more emotional debate this is the second of three 
articles on euthanasia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
that december night 3 years ago in the bahamas 
where darlena and bob risley had traveled in a last desperate 
journey in search of a miracle cure for her cancer she became so 
nauseous and dehydrated that the doctor had to be called 
at their apartment the doctor gave her one shot for the nausea 
and a second shot to kill the pain in her back and in her stomach 
that had swollen larger than during her pregnancy years ago 
a few hours later just before midnight on dec 5 1984 darlena 
reached up and put her arms out to her husband he held her at 
that moment darlena risley stopped breathing at age 41 
darlenas suffering haunted risley so much that he was prepared 
to help her die sooner had she asked him for a peaceful end to her 
life even though it would have been a crime he thought about that 
when he returned to california and about the many others who endure 
the pain of terminal illness 
six months after darlenas death the 54yearold los angeles 
attorney started a campaign to revise the california natural death 
act to legalize active euthanasia and allow physicians to give 
terminally ill patients lethal doses of drugs upon their request 
and under certain safeguards 
darlenas death inspired risley to found americans against human 
suffering the group fell more than 100000 signatures short of the 
number required by the may 8 deadline to get the issue on the 
california ballot for novembers election but it still managed to 
gather 250000 names 
the organization with another proeuthanasia group the los 
angelesbased national hemlock society is planning to try again in 
1990 not only in california but in oregon washington state and 
florida as well 
while support for active euthanasia is growing in some segments 
of the american population the opposition remains strong from 
leading experts on medical ethics lawmakers religious leaders 
doctors and lawyers 
as individuals and as a society we have the positive 
obligation to protect life said cardinal joseph bernardin 
leader of the roman catholic archdiocese of chicago in a recent 
speech we have the negative obligation not to destroy or injure 
human life directly especially the life of the innocent and the 
vulnerable 
four prominent physicians and experts on medical ethics spoke of 
perilous times for our profession in a commentary printed in 
the april 8 issue of the journal of the american medical 
association they cited efforts in court and legislatures to 
legalize killing by doctors if patients request it 
now is the time for the medical profession to rally in defense 
of its fundamental moral principles to repudiate any acts of 
intentional killing by physicians and their agents the 
commentary said we call on fellow physicians to say that we will 
not deliberately kill and we must say to the broader community 
that if it insists on tolerating or legalizing active euthanasia 
it will have to find nonphysicians to do its killing 
the commentary was in response to an article published in the 
journal in which a doctor whose name was withheld described how 
he killed a 20yearold woman named debbie with an injection of 
morphine the woman like darlena was dying of ovarian cancer 
the commentary was signed by willard gaylin president of the 
hastings center in briarcliff manor ny leon r kass professor 
in the committee on social thought at the university of chicago 
mark siegler director of the center for clinical medical ethics at 
the university of chicago and edmund d pellegrino director of 
the kennedy institute of ethics at georgetown university 
in a telephone interview gaylin said he is not opposed to 
withdrawing medication or treatment from a dying patient if thats 
what he wants or to giving him pain relievers even if it would 
hasten death 
but i dont think doctors should assume the responsibility for 
actually killing a patient he said if our society wishes to 
condone that i think it would be best if that were not the 
doctors role we do allow the patient to do it to himself suicide 
is no longer a crime in any of the 50 states abetting a suicide is 
in almost every state 
gaylin suggested that if the public decides that some people 
should have the option of euthanasia then it should be done by a 
family member as surrogate for the physician 
this is precisely what ran through bob risleys mind in the 
final days of his wifes life she wanted to live so much that she 
withstood surgery four times and chemotherapy as the cancer spread 
through her body she suffered the indignity of having a catheter 
inserted into her stomach for eight months through which 
chemotherapeutic fluids flooded her abdomen the doctor had given 
her only a year to live she survived for two 
a few days before she died she and risley had discussed what 
they would do if her pain became too great but no decision was 
made except in his own mind 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880627-0218 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
i had resolved that if she asked me to help her die i would 
have done that no matter what he says i knew at the time 
that would have been a crime in the bahamas as well as everywhere 
in the states 
but she never asked him i wasnt forced into that moral 
decision which many many other people have been forced into he 
says 
but even if the patient asks for a lethal dose of drugs it is 
still wrong to accede to the request according to the guidelines 
of the national conference of catholic bishops in washington 
it is still an act of homicide on the part of the agent still 
an attack on the dignity of human life says richard doerflinger 
director of the conferences office for prolife activities and 
that is something that no government thats established to protect 
life should be allowing 
referring to routine efforts to prevent suicides he says our 
society has a long tradition of respect for human freedom but we 
still send police officers to dissuade or grab people threatening 
to jump from a bridge out of respect for their lives 
essentially this situation is no different 
the church does approve doerflinger notes of withdrawing 
respirators and other lifesupport systems in some cases 
the church also teaches that its legitimate to withdraw 
extraordinary means of life support which are means that are 
considered excessively burdensome to the patient or which provide 
no benefit says doerflinger not every withdrawal of life 
sustaining treatment is seen as euthanasia 
doerflinger sees a growing support for euthanasia partly due to 
an aging population in the united states the average married 
couple has less than two children and the growing percentage of 
elderly people is being seen by others as more of a burden than 
they were in the past 
what opponents of legalized euthanasia fear is the potential for 
abuse and exploitation 
giles scofield staff counsel for concerned for dying a new 
yorkbased group concerned with care of the terminally ill says 
there is a danger of misreading a patients wants or needs and of 
doctors taking the easy way out 
were not convinced its necessary he says a lot of 
patients now have rights that arent being honored if patients 
knew that they could be taken off a respirator or refuse artificial 
nutrition without having to go to court in all likelihood they 
would not want physicianassisted suicide if doctors knew that 
an acceptable way of dealing with a terminally ill patient was to 
provide a lethal injection there might be a tendency to substitute 
that for compassionate care 
doerflinger says if active euthanasia were legalized it would 
go far beyond the limited population that would now be included in 
legislation proposed by americans against human suffering under 
which two doctors must agree that in their judgment the patient 
will die within six months 
i dont know of anyone who really thinks the killing of 
someone who is thought to have seven months to live could still be 
punished as firstdegree murder once youve established a policy 
that euthanasia for patients expected to die in six months is a 
public good doerflinger argues 
i dont see how society could continue to keep that arbitrary 
dividing line people who wanted euthanasia who expected to die in 
seven months eight months a year would claim that they are being 
denied their rights 
sissela bok the noted author and philosopher says legalized 
active euthanasia would be dangerous for any society 
i think it takes away a very powerful barrier that we have 
against one form of violence she says we need a barrier 
against different forms of violence but certainly violence against 
those who are unable to defend themselves it could be that some 
people would die in a process like this who would not want to die 
opponents also worry that legalized euthanasia would undermine 
trust in the doctors role as healer and lifesaver 
theres a difference between giving a patient a painkiller and 
giving a patient a patient killer says giles scofield 
people want to live as long as they can and want the benefit of 
the healing arts says bob risley but when things become hopeless 
so that there isnt anything else to do no more treatments then 
making people die through the natural dying process going through 
the agonies in the final few days seems rather fruitless 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
