tv audiences will soon get their first real 
chance to hear pianist vladimir feltsman who emigrated to america 
last summer after much publicized difficulties in getting out of 
russia on wednesday july 13 he will perform in a live from 
lincoln center telecast on pbs 
this will be my first purely musical tv event says the 
36yearold feltsman playing in the white house sept 27 and 
my debut at carnegie hall nov 11 were shown on the news a 
little i was on the 60 minutes show it was more talking than 
music 
the mostly mozart festival now in its 22nd year at avery fisher 
hall will open with feltsman on tuesday july 12 the program will 
be repeated on wednesday night and televised live 
mostly mozart is one of the leading music festivals in the 
world i am very pleased i have been invited says feltsman i 
will play mozarts piano concerto in b flat major the last by 
mozart he was composing it at the same time he was composing the 
magic flute it is an absolute masterpiece 
then frederica von stade will sing something and then we will 
do an aria by mozart together so i think it will be fun 
since arriving in america feltsman has played 60 performances 
this season has been very special for me he says because i 
am doing everything for the first time the first time in 
philadelphia israel new york chicago los angeles 
feltsman was considered one of the soviet unions best young 
pianists when he applied in april 1979 for an emigration visa 
that year he says 52000 soviet jews emigrated but his 
application was denied two hours after he applied moscow radio 
and tv stations were ordered not to play his records all his 
concerts were canceled for two years then for the next six years 
feltsman was allowed to give a few concerts one such in a factory 
where machinery all but drowned out his music 
on june 14 1982 feltsman supporters who knew him through 
recordings and european concerts scheduled his new york debut 
to publicize his plight misha dichter played that evening 
five years later feltsmans emigration was approved alice 
chandler president of the state university of new york in new 
paltz who had looked up feltsman when she visited russia 
telephoned to offer him a job feltsman his wife anna and son 
daniel arrived in new york last august 
their 5yearold son is settled into nursery school and already 
finds it easier to speak english than russian as for his and his 
wifes adjustment feltsman says we came here more or less well 
prepared we were not looking for some miracles we understand that 
it is a beautiful country with many problems which we all know 
paradise does not exist in the world as we also know for 
people of my occupation my mentality my psychology my ability 
im certain it is still the best place in the world 
