<DOCNO> AP880627-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when southern corn leaf blight wiped out 
15 percent of the us corn crop in 1970 at a cost of more than 1 
billion plant breeders scrambled and within two years found 
varieties resistant to the disease 
ironically it was the breeders who had helped to start the 
disaster 
aiming for better varieties they had unknowingly bred 
susceptibility to the blight into fully 80 percent of the nations 
corn crop without that genetic uniformity the blight would have 
done little damage 
the same reliance on uniform crops led to the irish potato 
famine of the 1840s and to the spread of a wheat disease in 1916 
that led herbert hoover to call for two wheatless days each week 
the danger is that it could happen again 
according to peter day director of the center for agricultural 
molecular biology at rutgers university too little is being done 
to prevent such epidemics 
what were concerned about is having backup ability to deal 
with future threats day said during a recent us department of 
agriculture conference on biotic diversity and germplasm 
preservation global imperatives 
germplasm is the breeders term for the hereditary 
information in plants or animals when breeders encounter a crisis 
like the southern corn leaf blight they search for 
diseaseresistance genes in domesticated and wild varieties of the 
threatened crop 
the united states has no naturally occurring wild varieties of 
its major food crops tomatoes come from central and south america 
wheat and barley from the middle east and soybeans from asia 
virtually every major food crop is native to some other part of the 
world 
the us is a havenot nation in terms of germplasm 
resources said henry shands director of the national plant 
germplasm system operated by the usdas agricultural research 
service weve got to have a certain amount of gene bank defense 
to protect our nations food supply in the future 
without those breeding resources shands said the agriculture 
systems are going to collapse we just dont have enough land 
collecting germplasm in foreign countries is often a politically 
delicate task complicated by what is usually called the 
northsouth debate this refers to the unwillingness of some 
tropical and semitropical countries rich in germplasm the south 
to export their resources to the industrialized nations the north 
many of the tropical countries complain they are forced to pay 
industrial nations a hefty price for seeds produced from the 
tropical countries own resources 
some have done more than complain ethiopia has largely cut off 
access to its germplasm resources for example and many nations 
that could help each other such as north korea and south korea 
refuse to exchange germplasm with one another because of the tense 
political relations between them 
the united states maintains germplasm collections around the 
country with a central repository the national seed storage 
laboratory in fort collins colo 
but not enough is being done to evaluate and use those genetic 
resources researchers say and the programs cover only plants no 
organized program exists to collect and store the germplasm of 
important farm animals 
unfortunately financial support for germplasm collection and 
evaluation is lacking shands said the national plant germplasm 
system budget increased from almost 14 million in 1986 to 265 
million this year but despite usda appeals no increases were 
proposed for next year 
additional funds are needed to speed the incorporation of 
disease resistance into food crops which reduces the need for 
pesticides improving food safety and water quality shands said 
whales receive enormous attention while seeds go unnoticed 
said lawrence busch of the university of kentucky some 
absolutely minute and totally unattractive grass might be as 
important as that whale 
for example a tall wild wheat collected in eastern turkey in 
1948 was found to carry genes that made domestic wheat resistant to 
common and dwarf bunt and made it better able to tolerate stripe 
rust snow mold and mildew said sherl dietz coordinator of the 
agricultural research services western regional plant introduction 
station in pullman wash 
the transfer of diseaseresistance genes from wild strawberries 
to commercial varieties has helped increase strawberry yields by 
300 percent since 1960 said dietz similar advances have been made 
in other crops 
part of the urgency in conserving germplasm comes from the 
escalating destruction of forests and other natural habitats around 
the world 
up to 20000 species of plants and animals become extinct each 
year because of land clearing urban development and overgrazing 
said waldemar klassen director of the agricultural research center 
in beltsville 
the loss of unique plants and animals will deny future 
generations the use of still undiscovered genes for new foods 
fibers and medicines and industrial raw materials he said 
with its limited resources the agricultural research service 
does the best it can to collect germplasm before it is lost shands 
said a botanist will go to pakistan soon for example to retrace 
ancient trade routes in search of citrus fruits and other crops 
that may have been planted by the traders who followed marco polo 
to the orient 
its possible crops that have been lost in europe and the middle 
east might survive in those isolated regions farmers are rapidly 
clearing the land there and the opportunity to search for unusual 
crops wont last long he said 
storing germplasm is a tricky business although its tempting 
to think of plant gene banks as libraries from which breeders can 
pluck genetic information they need gene banks differ from 
libraries in one important respect the gene banks are alive 
plant germplasm is stored largely in the form of seeds they 
last a long time nobody is quite sure how long 50 or 100 years 
might be a good guess depending on the species but they dont 
last forever 
at the national small grain collection in beltsville david 
smith oversees 108000 specimens of grains including wheat barley 
oats rye rice and triticale a wheatrye hybrid 
seeds are stored in small manila envelopes with a maximum of 
500 grams of seed about a pound kept on hand for each sample the 
envelopes are stored in metal boxes stacked on tall 
industrialstyle steel shelves in a room where the temperature is 
kept at 50 degrees fahrenheit 
breeders requesting samples are sent about 5 grams enough to 
grow a row about five feet long smith said when stocks run low 
seeds are planted and grown to replenish the seed supply 
that also provides an opportunity to further identify the 
genetic traits contained in the seeds but the process has a cost 
some genes in the original batch appear again in the new 
generation some dont every time you regenerate seeds you lose 
a little diversity says shands 
information on us germplasm is kept in a database called the 
germplasm resources information network or grin which is 
available to any plant breeder 
such resources will be essential to feed a world that will 
support 6 billion people by the year 2000 the worlds farmers will 
have to produce more food in one generation than has been produced 
in the entire 10000year history of agriculture said garrison 
wilkes of the university of massachusetts and maintaining genetic 
diversity will be a global imperative 
there will be no synthetic food wilkes said you cant 
look for substitute technology 
</TEXT>
