a person who begins shoplifting late in life may 
have a psychiatric problem that requires professional evaluation 
researchers say 
firstoffense shoplifting by people older than 60 has been 
increasing for more than a decade gary moak of the university of 
massachusetts medical school and coauthors write in the june issue 
of hospital and community psychiatry 
sociological data doesnt support the idea that economic 
hardship is to blame they said but among psychiatric 
explanations patients inability to reconcile the loss of a 
spouse or of their health job home or independence may lead to 
unconscious acting out to obtain symbolic compensation especially 
if the patient feels unfairly deprived of the loss 
