now entering her sophomore year at vassar college poughkeepsie 
ny she plans to spend her junior year in rome or florence 
studying art 
they are among tens of thousands of american students reversing 
a recent trend and going to foreign countries to study according 
to the institute of international education iie the nations 
largest education exchange agency 48483 students earned academic 
credit for studies outside the united states in 198586 up from 
27145 in 198283 nearly double the number in three years 
the study offered no explanation for the increase but 
administrators of studyabroad programs said that at least some 
students may be finding that study overseas is economical compared 
with the more expensive us schools where tuitions have been 
soaring throughout the 1980s 
beaver college in glenside pa is noted for studyabroad 
programs in which students from 225 us colleges participate the 
school is sending more than 1700 students from us campuses to 
study in the british isles and vienna this year said college 
president bette landman compared with 750 students in 198081 
