<TEXT>
the strength of the japanese yen has made toyko 
the worlds most expensive city for expatriates for the third 
straight year according to a survey of 103 cities worldwide 
released monday 
the japanese port city of osaka was a close second followed by 
the iranian capital tehran according to a biannual survey by 
business international a genevabased research and consulting firm 
the study uses a weighted index based on items including food 
alcohol household supplies tobacco utilities clothing and 
entertainment but excludes housing it is aimed at helping 
international companies determine costofliving differentials for 
their expatriate employees 
using new york as the base for the study with a value of 100 
tokyo had an index rating of 221 osaka 219 and tehran 192 the 
survey said 
new york was tied for 33rd place with chicago and san francisco 
the most expensive us city was los angeles in 30th place 
followed by washington dc 
the drop in value of the us dollar against european currencies 
continued to make european cities expensive for expatriates who are 
paid in the us currency the survey said 
oslo norway remained the most expensive european city in 
seventh place overall zurich switzerland was in ninth tied with 
dakar senegal and geneva in 10th place 
five african cities ranked in the top ten libreville gabon 
182 brazzaville congo 168 lome togo 154 abidjan ivory 
coast 151 and dakar 143 
latin american cities remained among the least expensive for 
expatriates despite massive inflation since inflation in most 
cities was offset by regular devaluation of their currencies the 
survey said 
caracas venezuela remained the least expensive city with an 
index value of 38 buenos aires argentina was just slightly more 
expensive with an index rating of 43 
survey results are based on exchange rates in effect on april 8 
a press release said 
