<TEXT>
the dollar has soared to its highest levels 
against european currencies in eight months but market watchers 
remained divided monday about whether the currencys weekslong 
rally represents a lasting reversal or a temporary blip 
fundamentally the dollar has now changed its trend and 
instead of trending lower all those years since 1985 the dollar is 
in an upward move asserted paul chertkow director of currency 
economics at the london investment firm hoare govett ltd 
but geoffrey dennis an international economist at james capel 
and co said markets have gotten themselves quite excited about 
the dollar shortterm we think were going to see new lows still 
after months of stability the dollar has jumped 5 percent 
against the british pound 44 percent against the japanese yen and 
37 percent against the west german mark in home currency markets 
since last monday 
the dollar surged monday to its highest point against the 
british pound since october the pound fell 4 cents to 17030 by 
late afternoon in europe from 17430 on friday on news of a 
worsethanexpected record british merchandise trade deficit in 
may 
the dollar jumped to 18185 west german marks from 18010 marks 
on friday also the highest level since october 
earlier in tokyo the dollar rose 200 yen to a closing 13170 
yen in tokyo its highest level since early december 
the dollar has been helped by improvements in the us trade 
deficit and strong demand for dollardenominated securities 
especially by the japanese 
in addition speculators have been able to push the dollar 
higher without a concerted effort by central banks to counter their 
attempt dealers said 
the us federal reserve did intervene a bit on monday selling 
dollars which along with a bit of profittaking took some steam 
out of the rally dealers said the west german bundesbank also 
intervened in a limited way as it has in recent weeks 
but the sessions intervention although a warning was not 
significant or concerted dealers said 
the dollar has been boosted by the communique issued at the end 
of the world economic summit in toronto last week which led the 
markets to believe that the seven major industrialized nations 
would tolerate a higher dollar to counter inflation 
the industrialized countries again reiterated their commitment 
to stabilize currency exchange rates which they first made in 
february 1987 in september 1985 they had agreed to push the 
dollar lower 
what were seeing is an acknowledgement by the group of seven 
countries following their meeting in toronto that they they have 
given some scope for the dollar to rise said tim odell senior 
international economist at the london investment firm phillips and 
drew ltd 
support also has come from growth in global demand for the 
dollar particularly from japanese financial institutions such as 
life insurance companies which are buying up us stocks and bonds 
again for the first time in months dealers said 
relatively high us interest rates have made dollardenominated 
investments more attractive analysts said 
the dollar remains strong even though interest rates in britain 
and west germany have been rising in recent weeks which would make 
investments in those countries more competitive 
the strong demand for the dollar underscored by high trading 
volume in the foreign exchange markets in turn has spurred 
speculative interest in the currency dealers said 
the gain has been feeding on itself since the dollar leaped past 
several psychological barriers such as 18 west german marks and 
130 japanese yen 
it was the release of betterthanexpected us trade data two 
weeks ago that set the scene for the dollars climb analysts said 
the commerce department reported on june 14 that the merchandise 
trade deficit narrowed to a seasonally adjusted 989 billion in 
april its lowest level since 1984 from 117 billion dollars in 
the previous month 
but the outlook for the dollar is unclear 
there is a lot more upside potential said the bullish 
chertkow forecasting a dollar of 19 marks and 135 yen 
but it is not known how high a level the central banks would 
allow 
there may be a level that is a new ceiling or a range agreed 
to in toronto odell said 
several dealers speculated that the central banks would not step 
in together until the markets recent bullishness was spent 
some analysts said the longterm trend is bearish because of the 
stilllarge us trade deficit fears of inflation in europe and 
the uncertainty presented by the us general election 
there isnt much scope for the dollar to rise on a sustained 
basis odell said 
